result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (5th or 6th) and Operating w/ PAC (5th or 6th). The defendant was found guilty of OWI (5th or 6th) and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (5th or 6th) was dismissed by the court.

  • Dena D Clark was found guilty of OWI (5th or 6th), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).
  • Dena D Clark was found guilty of Hit and Run-Involve Injury, an unclassified felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.67(1).
  • Dena D Clark was found guilty of Hit and Run-Involve Injury, an unclassified felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.67(1).
  • Dena D Clark was found guilty of Injury by Intoxicated Use/Vehicle, a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.25(1)(a).
  • Dena D Clark was found guilty of Injury by Intoxicated Use/Vehicle, a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.25(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

CLERK:  Laurie Brown
10:04 am  Defendant Dena D Clark appeared by video means from Ellsworth Correctional. Prosecuting Atty Diane M. Donohoo appeared for State of Wisconsin. Attorney Jeffrey L Hahn in court for Defendant Dena D Clark.
Defendant is moving for her counsel to be withdrawn.  Neither ADA Donohoo or Attorney Hahn object to motion.  Attorney Hahn is allowed to withdraw and will submit an order.
10:05 am  Attorney Hahn excused from motion hearing.
Defendant has filed a petition for earned release.
ADA Donohoo objects and refers to page 8, line 16 of sentencing transcript and also page 31, line 10 and page 33, line 16.
Defendant makes argument to the Court that DOC made her aware that she was a prime candidate for earned release program.  
At the time she was sentenced, she believed she was not statutorily eligible based on statements by her attorney as well as ADA Donohoo.  
Because of that belief she never argued for earned release at time of sentencing.
For reasons stated on the record, Court denies petition.  ADA Donohoo will prepare order.
